We are looking for a way to produce these wheels soft as described below. Can we produce them using a 3D printer and 90A TPU filament? Or should we use 60A instead?
https://imgur.com/a/t1LvJTX
https://imgur.com/a/yNRHHba

The lower durometer you use, the squishier the wheel will be. For reference, the compliant wheel you sent has a durometer of 35A.

Word of caution, though: the durometer is referring to the “squish” of the wheel, not the “grip”. Most TPU I’ve printed with hasn’t been very grippy, so it’s likely that they won’t intake nearly as well as standard compliant wheels - YMMV.

If you want these to be anything like most compliant wheels in FIRST, you should absolutely go with the 60A filament. Even that’s going to produce wheels that are about the hardest that are usually available as COTS parts. Many teams use compliant wheels that are more in the 45A to 35A range in order to get them to be as compliant as they want.

That first video you posted is from my team, so I’ll respond here. We had a student who was interested in 3D printing compliant wheels a few years ago, and he was able to develop a design that worked pretty well. The final design used clear TPU (don’t remember what durometer off the top of my head), an HDPE insert to avoid twisting on the hex axle, and a “bumpy” wheel surface to maximize grip. The project was really cool and he learned a lot, but at the end of the day it’s easier for us to just buy a stock of COTS compliant wheels from an FRC supplier than printing them custom every year.

Here’s a post I wrote about the project a few years ago when someone else asked a similar question:

Molding/Casting Custom Compliant and Solid Wheels Technical
In 2020 we experimented with printing compliant wheels out of TPU. They held up surprisingly well and were decently reliable. [image] We tried a number of different geometries, thicknesses, surface finishes, etc. [image] Eventually we settled on this wheel, which had an HDPE insert to help preserve the hex bore. [image] (I don’t have a picture of the assembled wheel with the insert, I’ll have to get one next time I’m in the shop) As far as I remember, it never made it into an official r…

I personally do not believe FDM/FFF is the correct technology for printing custom soft/flexible wheels. I’ve tried many different variations and while it is possible to do with FDM/FFF I’ve had much better results using vat photopolymerization technologies (SLA, DLP, etc.). My best results came from Loctite 3D IND402 printed on an Origin printer.

Recently, I printed a flexible wheel mold out of ASA on a FDM/FFF printer that turned out pretty well. I sprayed a bunch of mold release on it and used Mold Maker as my molding material. I don’t have a picture or video on me but I’ll take some tomorrow while I am at our Saturday meeting.

image543×526 72.8 KB

I’d be interested to see how TPU turns out in a powder-based process for this application.

We used TPU printed wheels, and I can confirm that they are not very grippy. A former student also cast silicone compliant wheels in a 3d printed mold, and although he did get very far with those particular experiments, he did produce some very tacky and extremely soft wheels. (One seemed to be half way between an AM compliment and jello) If you cast any larger ones, you are probably going to need some sort of rigid hub either cast in place or bolted to the compliment wheel.

I think 3D printing a sacrificial mold that you pour polyurethane into would be a more reliable way to make a custom soft wheel. This technique presents many of its own challenges that probably can’t be quickly overcome in a couple days of a build season, but it would let you use material that doesn’t have to be rigid before curing, which is the problem with printable rubbers.

I’ve made a ton of TPU printed compliant wheels, there are interesting things you can do in you wheel model or slicer settings to make them more grippy.
You can texturize the surface to add bumps, or use “Fuzzy Skin” to make the outside of the wheels rougher.
You can add velcro to the outside of the wheel, or an adhesive silicone mat to the outside (they sell these for FPV drones)
